blocks.text:
Before any formula, decide what the quoted number *is*:
- a **standard deviation** $s$ → it is *already* a standard uncertainty, $u=s$ (divisor 1);
- a **variance** $V$ → take the square root, $u=\sqrt V$;
- an **expanded uncertainty** $U$ → divide by its coverage factor, $u=U/k$;
- a **maximum spread / range / tolerance / resolution** → it is a **half-width** $a$ and takes a distribution divisor ($\sqrt3$, $\sqrt2$ or $\sqrt6$).
Misreading this classification is the single most common way to lose marks.

steps.content:
Three contributions:
- mass repeatability — **Type A** (statistics on 10 readings, mean reported);
- balance bias from the certificate — **Type B** (quoted expanded uncertainty);
- volume resolution — **Type B** (rectangular, half-width $a=r/2$).
Everything is already in coherent units (g, cm³), so no conversion is needed.
